SIMPLE: promontory
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Promontory
<hw>Prom"on*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Promontories</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[ L.
<ets>promonturium</ets>, <ets>promunturium</ets>; <ets>pro</ets> before
+ <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>, mountain: cf. F.
<ets>promontoire</ets>. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Phys. Geog.)</fld> <def>A high point of land or
rock projecting into the sea beyond the line of coast; a headland; a
high cape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like one that stands upon a <qex>promontory</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A projecting part. Especially:
<sd>(a)</sd> The projecting angle of the ventral side of the sacrum
where it joins the last lumbar vertebra. <sd>(b)</sd> A prominence on
the inner wall of the tympanum of the ear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Promorphological</ent>⟦br⟧
